'''Norman Henry Anderson''' (born July 23, 1925)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ruwTAAAAYAAJ&q=%22Anderson,+Norman+Henry%22+AND+%221925%22&dq=%22Anderson,+Norman+Henry%22+AND+%221925%22&hl=en&ei=9kLDTeiPM8-ftweg86zFBQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CEEQ6AEwBQ]</ref> is a social [[psychologist]], and Distinguished Professor Emeritus<ref name="UCSD2">{{cite web | url = http://psy.ucsd.edu/  | title = UCSD Psychology &#124; Home | format = | work = | accessdate = 2009-03-26}}</ref>  at the University of California, San Diego, where he was one of three founders of the Department of Psychology.<ref name="UCSD">{{cite web | url = http://psy.ucsd.edu/research/welcome.php | title = UCSD Psychology &#124; Research &#124; History | format = | work = | accessdate = 2009-03-25}}</ref>  He received a BS in 1946 and an MS in 1949 from the [[University of Chicago]], and an   MS in 1955 and a PhD in 1956 from the [[University of Wisconsin]],<ref name = "Yale1">{{cite book |title=Historical Register of Yale University, 1951-1968 |year=c. 1968 |publisher=Yale University |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=120 |url=https://books.google.com/books?q=%22Norman+Henry+Anderson%22&btnG=Search+Books&output=html |accessdate= }}</ref>  with a thesis on ''Effect of First-order Conditional Probability in a Two-choice Learning Situation''.<ref name = "thesis">{{cite book |title=Effect of First-order Conditional Probability in a Two-choice Learning Situation |last=Anderson |first=Norman  |year=1956 |publisher= [[University of Wisconsin]] |location=[[Madison, Wisconsin]] |isbn= |page= |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdVKAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Norman+Henry+Anderson%22&dq=%22Norman+Henry+Anderson%22&output=html |accessdate= }}</ref> Anderson also taught at The University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) during the 1960s and 1970s, and is credited with developing [[Information Integration Theory]].<ref>Berkowitz, L. and Anderson, N.H. (1978). Cognitive Theories in Social Psychology: Papers from Advances in Experimental Social Psychology. New York, NY, USA: Academic Press.</ref>

Anderson was the winner of the 1972 [[AAAS Prize for Behavioral Science Research]].<ref>[http://archives.aaas.org/awards.php?a_id=24 History & Archives:  AAAS Prize for Behavioral Science Research]</ref>

