{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Pontiac fever | synonyms = | image = | caption = | pronounce = | field = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Pontiac fever''' is an acute, nonfatal respiratory disease caused by various species of [[Gram-negative bacteria]] in the genus ''[[Legionella]]''. It causes a mild upper respiratory infection that resembles acute influenza. Pontiac fever resolves spontaneously and often goes undiagnosed. Both Pontiac fever and the more severe [[Legionnaire's disease]] are caused by the same bacteria, but Pontiac fever does not include pneumonia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hpa.org.uk/Topics/InfectiousDiseases/InfectionsAZ/PontiacFever/GeneralInformation/ |title=General Information- Pontiac Fever |publisher=HPA |date= |accessdate=2013-04-07}}</ref><ref>http://jid.oxfordjournals.org/content/191/9/1530.full.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jid.oxfordjournals.org/content/184/10/1289.full |title=Pontiac Fever Due to Legionella micdadei from a Whirlpool Spa: Possible Role of Bacterial Endotoxin |publisher=Jid.oxfordjournals.org |date= |accessdate=2013-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://legionellacontrol.com/legionella/pontiac-fever-legionnaires-disease/ |title=General Information- Pontiac Fever & Legionnaires’ Disease |publisher=Legionellacontrol |date= |accessdate=2011-09-02}}</ref>
Pontiac fever was named for [[Pontiac, Michigan]], where the first case was recognized. In 1968, several workers at the county's department of health came down with a fever and mild flu symptoms, but not pneumonia. After the [[1976 Philadelphia Legionnaires' disease outbreak|1976 Legionnaires' outbreak in Philadelphia]], the Michigan health department re-examined blood samples and discovered the workers had been infected with the newly identified ''[[Legionella pneumophila]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/01/health/01docs.html|title=In Philadelphia 30 Years Ago, an Eruption of Illness and Fear|date=1 August 2006|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.biocentral.com/1471-2458/6/112 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727065410/http://www.biocentral.com/1471-2458/6/112 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2014-07-27 |title=biocentral.com |publisher=biocentral.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-08 }}</ref> An outbreak caused by'' Legionella micdadei'' in early 1988 in the UK became known as [[Lochgoilhead]] fever.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(89)91319-6 | title=LOCHGOILHEAD FEVER: OUTBREAK OF NON-PNEUMONIC LEGIONELLOSIS DUE TO LEGIONELLA MICDADEI | journal=The Lancet | date=1989 | volume=333 | issue=8633 | pages=316–318 | first=DavidJ. | last=Goldberg}}</ref> Since that time, other species of ''Legionella'' that cause Pontiac fever have been identified, most notably in New Zealand, in 2007 where ''[[Legionella longbeachae]]'' was discovered. The New Zealand outbreak also marked the first time Pontiac fever had been traced to potting soil.
==Cause== Species of ''Legionella'' known to cause Pontiac fever include ''[[Legionella pneumophila]]'', ''[[Legionella longbeachae]]'', ''[[Legionella feeleii]]'', ''Legionella micdadei'', and ''[[Legionella anisa]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Phin|first1=Nick|title=Epidemiology and clinical management of Legionnaires' disease|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|date=2014|volume=14|issue=10|pages=1011–1021|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(14)70713-3}}</ref>
===Reservoir=== Sources of the causative agents are aquatic systems and potting soil. The first outbreak caused by inhalation of [[Aerosolization|aerosolized]] potting soil was discovered in New Zealand in January 2007. A total of 10 workers at a nursery came down with Pontiac fever. It was the first identification of ''L. longbeachae''.<ref>{{cite journal|title= An outbreak of Pontiac fever due to Legionella longbeachae serogroup 2 found in potting mix in a horticultural nursery in New Zealand|date=2013-01-30 |pmid=19781115 | doi=10.1017/S0950268809990835 |volume=138 |issue=1 |vauthors=Cramp GJ, Harte D, Douglas NM, Graham F, Schousboe M, Sykes K |journal=Epidemiol. Infect. |pages=15–20}}</ref>
===Transmission=== Pontiac fever does not spread from person to person. It is acquired through aersolization of water droplets and/or potting soil containing ''Legionella'' bacteria.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Lauri A. Hicks |author2=Laurel E. Garrison |url=http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2012/chapter-3-infectious-diseases-related-to-travel/legionellosis-legionnaires-disease-and-pontiac-fever.htm |title=Legionellosis (Legionnaires’ Disease & Pontiac Fever) - Chapter 3 - 2012 Yellow Book - Travelers' Health - CDC |publisher=C.cdc.gov |date=2011-07-01 |accessdate=2013-04-08}}</ref>
==Epidemiology== Pontiac fever is known to have a short incubation period of 1 to 3 days. No fatalities have been reported and cases resolve spontaneously without treatment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/legionella/clinicians.html |title=Legionella (Legionnaires' Disease and Pontiac Fever |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=CDC |publisher=Centers for Fisease Control and Prevention |access-date=4 June 2014 |quote=}}</ref> It is often not reported.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Pancer K, Stypulkowska-Misiurewicz H | year = 2003 | title = Pontiac fever – non-pneumonic legionellosis | url = | journal = Przegl Epidemiol | volume = 57 | issue = | pages = 607–12 }}</ref> Age, gender, and smoking do not seem to be risk factors. Pontiac fever seems to affect young people in the age medians of 29, 30, and 32. Pathogenesis of the Pontiac fever is poorly known.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Fraser DW, Deubner DC, Hill DL, Gilliam DK | year = 1979 | title = Nonpneumonic, short-incubation-period Legionellosis (Pontiac fever) in men who cleaned a steam turbine condenser | url = | journal = Science | volume = 205 | issue = | pages = 690–1 | doi=10.1126/science.462175}}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Friedman S, Spitalny K, Barbaree J, Faur Y, Mckinney R | year = 1987 | title = Pontiac fever outbreak associated with a cooling tower | url = | journal = Am J Public Health | volume = 77 | issue = | pages = 568–72 | doi=10.2105/ajph.77.5.568| pmc = 1647035}}</ref>
